1289","Abt 1316":"circa 1316","1316":"1316","1305":"1305","1304":"1304","about 1305":"circa 1305","1400":"1400","1289":"1289","1266":"1266","1343":"1343","1320":"1320","about 1289":"circa 1289","about 1320":"circa 1320","Cheadle, Staffordshire, England.":"Cheadle, Staffordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Cheadle, Cheshire, England":"Cheadle, Cheshire, England","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Drayton Bassett, Staffordshire, England":"Drayton Bassett, Staffordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Cheadle, Staffordshire, England":"Cheadle, Staffordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"abt 1289–":"about 1289–Deceased","1289–Female":"1289–Deceased","1285–1343":"1285–1343","1305–1370":"1305–1370","1316–1400":"1316–1400","1320–1394":"1320–1394","1242–Male":"1242–Deceased","1266–Female":"1266–Deceased","1242":"1242","1285":"1285","1394":"1394","1370":"1370","abt 1289":"about 1289","Abt 1316":"about 1316","1316":"1316","1305":"1305","1304":"1304","about 1305":"about 1305","1400":"1400","1289":"1289","1266":"1266","1343":"1343","1320":"1320","about 1289":"about 1289","about 1320":"about 1320","Cheadle, Staffordshire, England.":"Cheadle, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","Cheadle, Cheshire, England":"Cheadle, Cheshire, England","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","Drayton Bassett, Staffordshire, England":"Drayton Bassett, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","Cheadle, Staffordshire, England":"Cheadle, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Beaumont","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Gilles, Gaetan, Honore, Jacques, Jean-Guy, Marcel.","English (of Norman origin) and French: habitational name from any of the five places in Normandy or several others elsewhere in France so named. The placename comes from Old French <i>beu</i>, <i>bel</i> ‘fair, lovely’ + <i>mont</i> ‘hill’. There are also places in England so named under Norman influence in Cumberland, Lancashire, and Essex, the last of which changed its name in the 12th century from <i>Fulepet</i> ‘foul pit’ to <i>Bealmont</i> ‘beautiful hill’; these may also have given rise to the surname. The surname is now widespread throughout England, but most common in Yorkshire. Compare   Belmont  .","History: Many English bearers of this surname are descended from Henry de Beaumont (died 1340), who came to England from France as a soldier, serving Kings Edward I, II, and III of England. He acquired the earldom of Buchan in Scotland by marriage. — Many American bearers of this surname are descendants of John Beaumont (1612–47), who came to North America from England in 1630. William Beaumont came from England to Cambridge MA in 1635 and subsequently moved to CT."],"variants":[{"name":"Bement","meanings":["English (Cambridgeshire): variant of   Beaumont  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Beeman","meanings":["English (Kent): occupational name for a beekeeper, from Middle English <i>bee-man</i> ‘bee-keeper’ (Old English <i>bēo</i> + <i>mann</i>).","English (Kent): variant of   Beaumont  .","Americanized form of German   Biemann   or of its Dutch cognate <b>Bieman</b>."]},{"name":"Belmont","meanings":["French and English (of Norman origin): variant of   Beaumont  .","Catalan: habitational name from the placename Bellmont ‘beautiful mountain’. Compare Spanish   Belmonte  ."]},{"name":"Baumunk","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Siegmund.","German: probably a Germanized form of a French Huguenot name <b>Beaumont</b> (see also   Beaumont  )."]},{"name":"Bayman","meanings":["English (mainly Lancashire): variant of   Beaumont  .","Americanized form of German <b>Beumann</b> or <b>Bäumann</b>, variants of   Baumann  ."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Joan de Beaumont was born about 1289, in Cheadle, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, William de Beaumont, was 48 and her mother, Isabel, was 25. She married John Basset in 1304, in Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter."},"et":{"abt 1289–":"umbes 1289–Surnud","1289–Female":"1289–Surnud","1285–1343":"1285–1343","1305–1370":"1305–1370","1316–1400":"1316–1400","1320–1394":"1320–1394","1242–Male":"1242–Surnud","1266–Female":"1266–Surnud","1242":"1242","1285":"1285","1394":"1394","1370":"1370","abt 1289":"umbes 1289","Abt 1316":"umbes 1316","1316":"1316","1305":"1305","1304":"1304","about 1305":"umbes 1305","1400":"1400","1289":"1289","1266":"1266","1343":"1343","1320":"1320","about 1289":"umbes 1289","about 1320":"umbes 1320","Cheadle, Staffordshire, England.":"Cheadle, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cheadle, Cheshire, England":"Cheadle, Cheshire, England","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Drayton Bassett, Staffordshire, England":"Drayton Bassett, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cheadle, Staffordshire, England":"Cheadle, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"abt 1289–":"noin 1289–Kuollut","1289–Female":"1289–Kuollut","1285–1343":"1285–1343","1305–1370":"1305–1370","1316–1400":"1316–1400","1320–1394":"1320–1394","1242–Male":"1242–Kuollut","1266–Female":"1266–Kuollut","1242":"1242","1285":"1285","1394":"1394","1370":"1370","abt 1289":"noin 1289","Abt 1316":"noin 1316","1316":"1316","1305":"1305","1304":"1304","about 1305":"noin 1305","1400":"1400","1289":"1289","1266":"1266","1343":"1343","1320":"1320","about 1289":"noin 1289","about 1320":"noin 1320","Cheadle, Staffordshire, England.":"Cheadle, Staffordshire, Englanti, Yhdist